  "answer": "In Yājñavalkya Smṛti chapter 2 (work slug: unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6), the procedure for a witness who has lied in court is given at verses Yj_2.81–2.82. Yj_2.81 (paragraph p-dbd716) states: 'False witnesses should be punished separately with a fine double the amount in dispute; a Brāhmaṇa, however, is to be banished.' Yj_2.82 (paragraph p-71cfc7) adds: 'He who, having given testimony, later denies it to others, being overcome by darkness, shall be made to pay a fine eight times the amount; a Brāhmaṇa, however, should be banished.' An exception is given at Yj_2.83: where giving true testimony would certainly cause the death of a member of any varṇa, false testimony is permitted, and purification requires the twice-born to offer a sacrificial porridge to Sarasvatī.",
